    <note>Li(2) Tao(4) [13065] He fled with his father at the end of Tang. He became Hengyang ling under the Ma ruler of Chu, but when his elder cousin, Yu(10) [19565], took office under the Liang and Hou Tang, he traveled north and served Liang and was a chief minister under Later Jin and Han and was appointed Bingbu shangshu by Song Taizu. However, the only notice of his posts as chief minister are under the Later Han. His son remained behind in Xiangtan since he traveled alone to the North. See Su Song's inscription for his descendant, Chang [971]. Wan Sitong, Wudai Jiangxiang dachen nianpu (ERWSBB), p. 8. CBD, 2, 919-20.From Hartwell's ACTIVITY table:947:  Apt. Hanlin xueshi, Hubu shangshu, Zhongshu shilang (State Council)948:  Dismissed (ba) from State Council.                                                                                                                                                                                 ndant Li(2) Bing [8082], locates them in Caozhou, Jiyin (modern Caoxian) county until Jinggui, who moved to Jizhou, Juye county. I identify Tao(5) as making the move, but it probably took place much earlier. CBD, 2, 919-20. 《唐代人物知識ベース》記其生卒年為：898 - 961.</note>
